description: This issue marks the first appearance of Stanley and His Monster

deck: The first issue of Weird War Tales.
description:
War couldn't be even more disturbing than this. Weird War Tales collects the stories from one of Vertigo's finest writers, all focusing on war themes, with bizarre and terrifying plot twists. These stories include the following:

"The Willow Warriors" is a story of an eternal confrontation between two shoguns who, after their factions' continuous failure to earn victory, have decided to send their most powerful fighters to settle the battle.

"The Survivor" tells the tale of a World War II captain encountering an army of killer creatures, who just massacred his entire group after a brief meeting with a delusional shipwreck survivor.

"Tunnel Rats" recalls the frightening life of a soldier who fought the Vietnamese War and during his escapades with his fellow comrade, discovers an underground city full of cannibalistic people who were hiding under the surface for years. And...

"Ares", which talks about a gang member on a mission to seek retribution for his gang and afterwards, gets an encounter with the Norse god of war, Ares, after his mission didn't become a sucess.
name: Book One

deck: The second issue of Weirs War Tales.
description:
New writers and a whole lot of nasty comes your way as Vertigo unleashes another anthology of war-terror, that is, the second issue of Weird War Tales. This issue contains the following stories:

"The Elopment" is about a prisoner of war's encounter with a woman disguising as a man, who plots to escape their incarceration and the man's struggle to return to the woman after she was murdered in a prison riot.

"Mightier" is a wordless presentation which shows a simple signing of the man in power, which is the unnamed President of the United States in this story, means the death of several innocents in a split second. And...

"Looking Good, Feeling Great" is about a wannabe soldier boy who goes on a bloody killing spree against those who ever underestimated him after being rejected several times by the army.
name: Book Two

description: Historians wonder: Did Leonardo ever take a lover? A painful episode from the artist's youth reveals an intimate secret.

Return with us now to those thrilling days of yesteryear, as we re-present the adventures of Ogden Whitney's Fat Nothing. This issue reprints two classic tales in color for the first time. Plus, a brand new eight-page Herbie story written and illustrated by none other than John Byrne! Don't miss this one - you want he should bop you with that there lollipop?
name: Herbie

description: Tom McWeeney and Rich Hedden take the plump lump on a brand new adventure into a famous mansion full of beautiful girls...all swooning over Herbie! Also, two classic Ogden Whitney tales, "Big Fat Mess at the Okay Corral!" and "George Washington's Teeth!" It's history, as only Herbie can make it!
name: Herbie
